:: Start
In Bologna, and you are Caterina, seventeen years old, standing inside the silent vastness of the Istituto delle Scienze.
The museum stretches endlessly around you, glass cases filled with preserved animals, strange instruments, cracked globes, 
and objects that feel half scientific, half impossible. As you move deeper, the silence begins to shift—not break, 
but bend—because now there is something else inside it. A smell. Coffee. Warm, fresh, and completely out of place in a building this old.

[[Follow the smell deeper into the building -> The Study]]
[[Stay and examine the exhibits around you -> The Museum Memory]]

:: The Museum Memory
You slow down, letting your curiosity drift through the glass cases as you pass relics of strange knowledge: a whale jawbone resting 
like something too large to belong indoors, a rusted compass that has forgotten direction, and a cracked globe marked with faded journeys 
that no longer connect to anything real.
A brass plaque catches your attention—Luigi Ferdinando Marsili. The name lingers without explanation,
as if it expects you to already know it. And yet even as you stand there, the smell of coffee returns, stronger now, 
threading upward through the corridors like something calling you back to where you should have gone first.

[[Follow the coffee smell -> The Study]]

:: The Study
You follow the scent upward until the corridors narrow and the silence thickens, ending at a half-open door where warm light spills into the hallway. 
Inside, you hear the soft sound of movement, the faint clink of porcelain, and something that feels like presence before it becomes sight.
The room inside is crowded in a way that feels intentional rather than messy—maps layered across walls, glass jars filled with unknown substances, 
and sketches of cannons spread across a desk like fragments of a mind thinking too much at once. 
Behind it sits an old man who looks up at you not with surprise, but recognition, as if you were expected.
He gestures to a chair, and when you sit, he lifts a small porcelain cup.
“Coffee?”
Then he gives his name: Luigi Ferdinando Marsili.
And suddenly the room changes, because names like that are not just names—they are histories. Explorations. Wars. 
Knowledge. And now, all of it is sitting in front of you, asking you where you want to begin.

