:: I. The Boy in Bologna
Marsili leans back in his chair, turning the small porcelain cup slowly between his fingers before speaking again. “I was born here in Bologna in 1658, 
only a few streets from this room, and from the moment I arrived, my future had already been planned for me.” His father, Carlo Marsili, and his mother,
Margherita Hercolani, belonged to two old noble families whose histories stretched across generations of titles, marriages, and carefully protected reputations. 
From birth he inherited the title of count, though even now the idea seems faintly ridiculous to him. “A title given at birth is only clothing,” he says. 
“People admire it before they know whether the person wearing it has earned anything at all.”
The path prepared for him was simple: university, scholarship, politics, respectability. With the oldest university in the world standing almost outside 
his door, everyone expected him to follow it willingly. Instead, he resisted it more with every passing year. He hated the thought of spending his life 
repeating what other men had already written and calling that discovery. “They wanted me to study the world indirectly,” he says quietly, “when all I 
wanted was to step into it myself.” Still, curiosity kept pulling him toward knowledge, and so he attended lectures unofficially, slipping into crowded halls 
to listen from the back like a thief borrowing an education that did not belong to him. He listened to scholars discuss anatomy, astronomy, medicine, and plants,
yet never enrolled, never graduated, and never became the respectable scholar his family expected.

Marsili studies you for a moment before asking, “Tell me honestly—would you rather understand the world through books alone, or through experience, 
risk, and direct encounter with things that do not care whether you survive them?” Whatever answer you choose, he smiles as though he already knows it. 
Years later, after travels and discoveries carried him far beyond Bologna, Sir Isaac Newton introduced him to the Royal Society and called him eminent before
some of the greatest minds in Europe. The memory still amuses him. “I nearly laughed,” he admits, “because all I could think about was the frightened boy hiding 
at the back of lecture halls in Bologna, terrified someone might ask him a question he could not answer.”

